{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[8]", "headings": "['5. Conclusion']"}, "page_content": "5. Conclusion\nThe training method was validated using data from the Swedish national travel survey. We conducted a comparison between the benchmark model, trained on complete data, and models, trained on data with varying levels of missing information. The population generated from all the trained models was evaluated at the attribute-level and higher kdimensional levels to assess the model's capability in generating sampling and structural zeros. For all the evaluation metrics, the results obtained from the trained WGAN-GP on incomplete data exhibit a high degree of similarity with the benchmark WGAN-GP model trained on complete data. The validation results affirm the efficacy of the suggested training technique employing a mask matrix in proficiently managing incomplete data, leading to synthetic populations that closely resemble the real population.\nThe paper makes a substantial contribution to the field by providing a strong solution for population synthesis using incomplete data. The new finding opens up new areas for research in the future and shows how deep generative models can improve population synthesis, which is important for ABMs used in transportation simulations and other areas.", "type": "Document"}}